n international tests.”&#10;While I don’t dispute the figures, I think that pontneuf is overlooking the fact that most OECD countries have a centralized educational system, with teachers and school administrators being hired and fired by the national government - contrasted with the USA's patchwork of locally run schools (some only have one teacher), and different standards and results from county to county, and from district to district, and from state to state. We need at minimum state Core Standards, and Federal Core Standards would be better. &#10;As other posters have stated, teachers are more highly respected and supported by the citizens and teacher training program s in many OECD countries.&quot; &#10;Pontneuf is also overlooking the fact that unlike OECD countries, teachers in America are often badmouthed by conservatives. Who would want to work in a profession where there is a large vocal segment that us unsupported? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1227" language="en" documentId="128" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="TheSkeptic2" date="7/29/2013 11:25 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375133139-445-466" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="128" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="240"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="241" end="326"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="327" end="852"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="853" end="1004"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="1005" end="1227"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>